WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.120
I'm going to introduce myself in the Maori language to connect with the community

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:10.240
and to recognize the importance of indigenous culture in my work.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:38.240
So for those of you who don't speak Te Reo Maori, and I'm a beginner myself, hello everyone.

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:43.200
My ancestors hail from Cymru, Wales.

00:00:45.439 --> 00:00:49.360
I arrived in Aotearoa, New Zealand in 2019.

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:57.360
I currently live in Tamaki Makaurau, Auckland, and my name is Lee.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:03.759
So I work for Auckland Council, from the beautiful country of Aotearoa, New Zealand,

00:01:03.759 --> 00:01:10.080
from where I've flown to be here with you. But New Zealand had a pretty tough start to 2023.

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:18.160
So on the 25th of January, Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern announced her resignation,

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:23.199
which came as a surprise to just about everyone. She looks very happy here, but it was quite a sad time.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:32.720
And then just two days later, Auckland experienced some of its worst flooding in living memory.

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:38.239
This image is taken from the inside of Auckland International Airport on that day.

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:46.080
And then just two weeks after that, a severe tropical cyclone was bearing down on the country,

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:51.599
Cyclone Gabriel, which you can see here approaching the top of the North Island.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:58.320
So I was working from home on that day, as was just about everybody that I knew,

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:03.839
when I got a call from somebody at work, and the conversation went something like this.

00:02:05.279 --> 00:02:10.800
Hi, he said. I work for Auckland Emergency Management. I manage the rostering team,

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:16.880
and we need to coordinate our volunteers so we can distribute them across the emergency

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:21.759
shelters tomorrow, after the cyclone has hit, to help our communities in need.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:28.160
We're currently using a big Excel spreadsheet to manage this, and it's kind of chaotic.

00:02:29.119 --> 00:02:33.360
Somebody told me that you're sort of good with data, so could you help us?

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:39.360
We need it by 6am tomorrow. What do you reckon?

00:02:41.839 --> 00:02:48.160
So I looked out of my office window at the giant elm tree as it was leaning towards my house and

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:52.800
back again. I sat down. I took a deep breath.

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:58.479
OK, I said. Here's what I can do.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:07.839
Now, I realised three significant things in this moment. It was a significant moment for me,

00:03:07.839 --> 00:03:12.559
and there were three things that I realised. To understand the first of those things,

00:03:12.559 --> 00:03:19.360
we need to go back again three years to January 2020, because the first of those things

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:25.360
is proficiency, which I define as delivering quality at pace.

00:03:27.039 --> 00:03:31.600
So in January 2020, I first started working for Auckland Council. It was actually my first

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:37.600
job in New Zealand, having moved there the previous year, and I was pretty excited to start

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:44.720
as a senior data analyst in the libraries and information department. So I'm autistic, and

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:50.800
this job helped me to combine two of my special interests, data and books. So I was really excited.

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:58.320
On my first week, my manager sat me down and she said, I need your help with something.

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:06.000
We need to report some numbers to the lead team, but these numbers are the data sources,

00:04:06.399 --> 00:04:10.080
lots of different spreadsheets, 20 different spreadsheets that are all in different places,

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:15.440
and surprise, surprise, they're all formatted differently. Can you bring all of that together

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:20.959
into one data set and visualise it for the lead team? And by the way, we need to do that every

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:30.640
month. What do you reckon? So I sat down, I took a deep breath. Now, I knew before I moved to

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:35.119
Auckland, I knew that R had been invented in Auckland. Some of you might know that.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:44.559
It was invented in part by this guy, Ross Ihaka, along with his colleague, Robert Gentleman,

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:50.000
back in the 1990s. This wasn't the reason I moved to Auckland, by the way, that R was

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.200
invented there. There's another story behind that. So I knew that R was invented in Auckland.

00:04:55.200 --> 00:05:01.600
And so I naturally assumed that all of the people working with R in Auckland Council would just be

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:10.559
churning out R scripts all day, right? Wrong. The most common tool and use in the team I worked in

00:05:10.559 --> 00:05:18.880
was, can anybody guess? Excel. Yeah. Along with a bit of SQL and a bit of Power BI, but mainly

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:25.839
Excel. Now, I knew that if I were to do what my manager was asking me to do using Excel,

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:34.160
then that would become my job. I would be spending days every month copying and pasting between Excel

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:39.920
spreadsheets and it would be demoralising. I didn't want it to become my job. So I thought,

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:44.480
well, R was invented here in Auckland. I work for Auckland Council, so I'll just do it in R.

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:51.359
The problem was, in January 2020, I'd never written a line of R code. So I taught myself R.

00:05:53.359 --> 00:05:56.559
One of the reasons I chose R was not just because it was invented in Auckland,

00:05:56.559 --> 00:06:01.760
but because of the incredibly supportive R community and the wonderful array of free,

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:06.399
freely available resources online, which made this process so much easier.

00:06:08.399 --> 00:06:12.880
Which includes this amazing book, which I'm sure many of you here are familiar with,

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:17.679
Alpha Data Science, really helped me along this journey, and I still refer to it all these years

00:06:17.679 --> 00:06:24.239
later. Incredibly helpful. As well as Tidy Tuesday, for those of you who know that,

00:06:24.239 --> 00:06:29.279
as well as Dave Robinson's Tidy Tuesday screencast on YouTube. He doesn't do them anymore,

00:06:29.279 --> 00:06:33.440
but they're still really worth watching. They were really helpful. So there were loads of

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:38.959
different resources that helped me along in that journey, such that within about six weeks or so,

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:47.040
six weeks or so, I had written my first R script. Yay. It was terrible. The code was awful.

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:53.760
But it worked. It worked, which meant that this thing that would have taken me a couple of days

00:06:53.760 --> 00:07:00.320
every month took less than an hour. So I'd saved all of that time. But then at the end of this,

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:03.519
I asked myself, but was it worth the time? Because I've just spent six weeks doing that.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:11.359
So I often refer to this XKCD comic that some of you might have seen. And this is actually the

00:07:11.359 --> 00:07:15.839
background on my work laptop, because I'm always tempted to improve processes, and I have to kind

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:21.679
of go, no, Lee, hold on. Is it worth doing this? This particular process was a monthly process.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:28.959
I spent about six weeks on it. And if you look at this chart, it was definitely worth putting

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:36.320
in that time to improve this process. I saved a lot of time. And I was so enthused by this that

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:41.359
I started automating all the things, any data wrangling process that came my way,

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:47.119
building R script. More and more R scripts started to accumulate, which was great.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:54.559
And so as time went on, I became better and better, and I became faster, and my code became

00:07:54.559 --> 00:08:01.920
better and better. And then in 2021, I joined an R-Ladies, I think it was an R-Ladies Melbourne

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:12.640
virtual webinar, where Fonty Carr, who might be here today, led a session on building your first

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:18.000
R package, which Seth has already nodded to from the session of last year's PositConf.

00:08:19.119 --> 00:08:23.279
Prior to that session, I thought that building R packages was like something that software

00:08:23.279 --> 00:08:28.880
engineers did. But it's not. I mean, it is as well. But if you want to get started,

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:34.320
it's not as hard as you think. So that webinar got me started.

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:41.679
This book, which Seth also acknowledged, if two people independently are recommending the same

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:46.080
things to you, you should probably check them out. This book was also really, really helpful,

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:54.320
R packages, as well as the building tidy tools workshop from PositConf 2022,

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:59.359
Emma Rand and Ian Little. You can find all the material online. Amazing. Highly,

00:08:59.359 --> 00:09:04.159
highly recommend that as well. All the links for this stuff, by the way, will be in my GitHub,

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:08.719
which I'll show you at the end. So I started building R packages. I started taking these

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:13.280
scripts that I'd written and packaging them, which meant that I had better documentation,

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:19.440
I had unit tests, all that good stuff. And it was great. So as 2021 went into 2022,

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:28.000
I now felt pretty good about what it was that I was building. I felt proficient. I wasn't an expert.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.159
There are very many people, many of whom were in this room, are much better at writing R code than

00:09:32.159 --> 00:09:39.039
me. But I didn't feel like an imposter anymore. I felt proficient. Which brings us back to February

00:09:39.039 --> 00:09:45.200
2023, as that cyclone was approaching and I got that phone call. I knew I could help

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:49.280
because I was proficient. I knew I could do this quickly because of that proficiency.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.880
I knew that it wouldn't be perfect, but let's be honest, anything's better than Excel.

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:03.760
So that was pretty good. As the storm approached and there were these winds all around the house,

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:09.039
the house was shaking, the Elm tree was leaning towards the house, and I was churning out this R

00:10:09.039 --> 00:10:15.039
code to build something better. And it was fairly simple. It was just a data frame that listed all

00:10:15.039 --> 00:10:18.719
the emergency shelters and all the shifts for each of those shelters and grouped them by different

00:10:18.719 --> 00:10:24.640
regions, connected that to somewhere where the rostrum team could access it and have more control

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:32.239
over allocating volunteers. It was pretty simple, but I did it. And then I realized the second thing

00:10:32.239 --> 00:10:39.359
as I reflected on that the following day, which was about business value, which I define as

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:46.960
advancing the organization's mission. So business value is a bit of a nebulous concept sometimes,

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:55.440
particularly if you work in the nonprofit sector or public sector. So I work for Auckland Council

00:10:55.440 --> 00:11:00.320
and defining business value can sometimes be a little tricky when you're working in the data

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:06.000
space because you don't always see the impact that your work is necessarily having. But here

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:12.239
was a perfect example of direct impact from a solution that I had built using my R skills,

00:11:12.239 --> 00:11:17.440
using my data skills. So I felt pretty good about that. And then I started to reflect on the previous

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:21.440
few years and realized that I'd actually been delivering business value all along,

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:26.960
albeit indirectly. So I automated a process, which meant that I freed up my time, which meant that I

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:34.479
could automate another process and deliver things as well. So I was delivering direct business value

00:11:34.479 --> 00:11:41.119
and indirect business value. But also along that journey, I had written a whole bunch of code that

00:11:41.119 --> 00:11:48.239
I never used that was a little bit self-indulgent. I just had fun writing the code. And in those

00:11:48.239 --> 00:11:55.760
situations, it's a bit like a pointless box. It's beautifully crafted. It's pretty cool,

00:11:56.479 --> 00:12:04.880
but it's maybe a bit pointless. Or is it? Because this is the sort of paradox of business value in a way.

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:12.640
In order to increase business value, you need greater proficiency.

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:18.320
But increasing proficiency doesn't always necessarily increase business value.

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:25.119
So, Baffle. I want to keep this family friendly. So if you don't know what that means,

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:30.960
feel free to Google it afterwards. But essentially, in order to get better at something, you just have

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:36.159
to play around. You have to experiment. You have to try things that will fail that might not lead

00:12:36.159 --> 00:12:42.239
anyway. But you learn from that. And then down the line, you can apply that learning to deliver that

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:49.760
business value. So, business value can be direct, indirect, or maybe deferred, maybe delayed as you're

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:59.359
learning. So, I was at this point where I could quickly create a new solution, where I was

00:12:59.359 --> 00:13:04.400
delivering business value. And I felt really good. I felt like, hey, I'm the expert. I've got all this

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:11.520
knowledge. They came to me. Awesome. So, I'm going to go ahead and create a new business value.

00:13:13.039 --> 00:13:16.960
As I was practicing this talk with somebody the other day, they said,

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:21.599
you're sounding pretty egotistical at this point, which is true.

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:29.200
And that was the third realization that I'd had, which is this thing that I'd built,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.320
if the cyclone had swept me away, and this thing broke or needed to change,

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:38.239
I didn't know anybody else who could do that at the organization.

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:41.280
In other words, it wasn't a sustainable solution,

00:13:43.599 --> 00:13:51.919
which brings me to sustainability. So, what is sustainability? In a nutshell, to me, it just means

00:13:52.799 --> 00:14:00.000
just share things. Share your knowledge. Share what you know. Share what you've built. Share

00:14:00.559 --> 00:14:06.239
where you've learned things. Share the shortcuts along the way. Just share as much as you possibly

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:14.799
can. And that was the realization I had on that night, was I had gained so much value from the

00:14:14.799 --> 00:14:19.440
R community. I had benefited from what that community was sharing with me, but I wasn't

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:25.679
sharing back. And I was really letting my community down of Aucklanders by not building

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:32.239
sustainable solutions. So, I needed to change the way that I was operating. And I was in a really

00:14:32.239 --> 00:14:38.479
fortunate position in February 2023, because just a few weeks later, I was seconded into my

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:43.599
manager's role. And so, now I was working with a team of data analysts that I had previously been

00:14:43.599 --> 00:14:49.039
in. And so, I had this nine-month window of opportunity to help them along on that journey,

00:14:49.679 --> 00:14:56.000
to share with them what I had learned, where I had learned it, and the shortcuts along the way.

00:14:56.960 --> 00:15:01.119
And it's really easy to share when you write code. I love this quote from Geoffrey Sanova,

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:06.640
who invented PowerShell. He says, the mouse is antisocial, the GUI is antisocial. So,

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:10.719
what does that mean? You have a problem to solve, and you solve it with the GUI,

00:15:10.719 --> 00:15:15.679
and what do you have? Problem solved. But when you solve it with a command line interface and

00:15:15.679 --> 00:15:20.559
a scripting environment, you have an artifact. And that artifact can be shared with someone.

00:15:20.559 --> 00:15:26.960
And I had built an entire ecosystem of artifacts that I could share with that team. And as time

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:31.840
went on, they started to contribute to those artifacts themselves. And they started to build

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:38.880
their own artifacts. This was amazing. And so, we had sustainable solutions, and we had this

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:46.320
more sustainable culture. And I went a bit further. I created an internal R package that

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:50.080
made things easier for them to work with some of our internal data.

00:15:50.880 --> 00:15:55.200
And I built a package that made it easier to build packages called PackagePal, which is on Crayon,

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:58.640
if you want it. It's just a checklist that tells you these are the things you should think about

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:08.080
when you're building an R package. So, that was great. And so, the end of this journey.

00:16:08.719 --> 00:16:16.719
The end of this journey. A mature data culture is based on proficiency, business value,

00:16:17.359 --> 00:16:26.559
and sustainability. But remember, proficiency takes time and practice. There are no shortcuts.

00:16:28.719 --> 00:16:33.599
Business value is important, but increasing proficiency sometimes comes at the expense

00:16:33.599 --> 00:16:41.679
of delivering value. And that's okay. Sustainability is a choice that puts the

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:50.960
needs of our community ahead of our own. Ultimately, in order to create a mature

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:56.719
culture, we need all of these things in place. But a mature data culture is one where

00:16:56.719 --> 00:17:03.280
individual practitioners have the space to grow and the time to share. And everyone benefits from

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:05.359
that. Thank you.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:22.719
Thank you, Lee. Really appreciate that. Really like that idea that the value could be deferred.

00:17:22.719 --> 00:17:26.719
I never thought about it that way. You practice and the business value is just deferred,

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:32.560
even though just because you're getting the proficiency. As we were waiting here to get

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:38.400
some questions in, I actually do have a question. I may not be specific to what the subject was,

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:42.560
but what happened to the elm tree? Did it survive? That's a bit of a sad story. So,

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:47.760
it did survive the cyclone, but then it sort of contracted Dutch elm disease and we had to

00:17:47.760 --> 00:17:53.680
cut it down. So, sorry. Sad ending. That's sad. I was hoping it would survive.

00:17:54.479 --> 00:18:02.400
It survived the night. The first package that you were able to write for your team

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:06.640
internally, where was it published? Was it published on GitHub or did you have a way of

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:11.839
being able to share internally? Yes. So, I published it on a private GitHub

00:18:12.479 --> 00:18:18.079
repo. And so, then I added my team into the organization account I created and then they

00:18:18.079 --> 00:18:23.760
could just install the package from the GitHub repo in R using... There's a package that makes

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:27.680
that really easy to install. So, yeah, there were a couple of them that I did make public.

00:18:27.680 --> 00:18:32.160
They were more kind of general use, but then we also had a bunch of internal private ones.

00:18:32.719 --> 00:18:35.359
That's great. Well, thank you again. Appreciate it.

00:18:35.359 --> 00:18:40.400
Thank you. Thank you, Lee.

